{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478592"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:13:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:13:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17523"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17523"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.78,0.01,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10213"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71130"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10213","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10213"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17523"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56601"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"9624"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23895"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71130"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-month-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent concerned about the appearance of his legs. He started walking at 12 months of age. He is growing well and meeting all developmental milestones. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His diet includes formula milk and regular solid foods. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he has an abnormal lower limb examination and is diagnosed has having genu varum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes his diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inward bowing of legs with knees touching and ankles apart","Outward bowing of legs with knees apart and ankles together","Forward bowing of legs with knees projecting anteriorly","Backward bowing of legs with knees projecting posteriorly","Rotational deformity with feet pointing inward"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with genu varum, which is characterised by \u003Cstrong\u003Eoutward bowing of legs with knees apart and ankles together\u003C/strong\u003E. This creates a distinctive \u0027bow-legged\u0027 appearance. When measured, the distance between the knees (intercondylar distance) with ankles together provides an objective measure of the severity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInward bowing of legs with knees touching and ankles apart\u003C/strong\u003E describes genu valgum (knock knees), which is a different condition that typically develops after age two years and is also commonly physiological.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForward bowing of legs with knees projecting anteriorly\u003C/strong\u003E describes genu recurvatum, which is hyperextension of the knee joint. This is not a normal finding and requires evaluation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBackward bowing of legs with knees projecting posteriorly\u003C/strong\u003E would describe knee flexion deformity, which is not a normal finding and suggests pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotational deformity with feet pointing inward\u003C/strong\u003E describes in-toeing, which is a separate condition related to femoral or tibial torsion or metatarsus adductus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysiological genu varum is common in children under age two years and typically resolves spontaneously. It is thought to result from intrauterine positioning and typically improves as the child grows and develops. The key is to distinguish physiological from pathological causes, which include rickets, skeletal dysplasias, and Blount disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Genu varum (bow legs) refers to outward bowing of the legs with knees apart when ankles are together","Physiological genu varum is common in children under age two years and typically resolves spontaneously","The intercondylar distance is used to measure the severity of genu varum"],"references":["National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI). MedGen: 154257 - Genu varum [Internet]. Bethesda (MD): National Library of Medicine (US); . Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/medgen/154257"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56601"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17523"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56601"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T12:21:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T12:22:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10213"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71130"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11